<br>
As for your specific points:<br>
<br>
Firstly we use a MT, an ST (second tank/backup tank) and one or two split tanks. ST shouldn't be a split tank IMO.<br>
<br>
- ST(BT) should NOT taunt on mobs, as successful taunt puts you at the top of the hate list rather than boost your aggro a bit. At most the ST should just stand in close proximity to the mob to generate some additional taunt.<br>
<br>
- MT should be the assist yes - although as I said I find it better to have a dedicated ST and other tanks as split tanks that way you have it covered if the MT dies whilst still having adds covered without confusion.<br>
<br>
Usually you kill adds first then the main mob - in HoT though there aren't really any main mobs (cept Dozzy) so the main target would remain the mob the MT is on and just have one person off-tank an add. With experience though you prioritise mobs (like white wurms first) but you'll wipe anyway first few times there if you get adds <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
- Positioning is mob-dependant. For wurms we wedge them in a corner, for the other stuff we surround them and people adjust during the fight to keep them from moving too much.<br>
<br>
- Rogues should evade every chance they get and monks FD from time to time - other than that if people pay attention to prox aggro and the MT has OK weapons then holding aggro shouldn't be a problem. If say another warrior continually gets aggro off the MT then they are screwing up not the MT.<br>
<br>
- HoT teaches you mob positioning as you really have to hide the non-melee from the wurm AE. Part of that is debuffers getting used to running right up to the mob to debuff so they don't risk pulling it out of position. Other casters also need to learn not to over-nuke and if they get summoned they back up slowly and try and lose aggro or they die - they don't run away and take the mob with them.<br>
<br>
HoT's great for teaching this and for refining aggro control - if your guild is totally new at aggro control though you'll have a rough time in HoT until you learn it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/uaakla2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>aakla2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Seasoned Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 227<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/24/02 8:49:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthebattlefield.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1305.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_sword.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Looking for a good guide to aggro/MT...</span><hr size=1> The only think you need MT's for are the Flurydrakes and the named dragons. everything else you can pretty much F8.<br>
